# Status

Get a fast overview of project health across multiple dimensions.

## Checks

Run these sequentially. Stop early if a critical issue is found.

### 1. Git state

```bash
git status --short
git log --oneline -5
git branch -vv           # show tracking info
```

Report: clean/dirty, unpushed commits, current branch, tracking status.

### 2. Build health

Run a quick build check (not a full build):

| Stack | Command |
|-------|---------|
| Rust | `cargo check --all-targets` |
| TypeScript | `tsc --noEmit` |
| Python | `python -m py_compile <main_file>` |

Report: compiles/errors.

### 3. Test health

Run the test suite:

| Stack | Command |
|-------|---------|
| Rust | `cargo test` |
| Node.js | `npm test` |
| Python | `pytest --tb=no -q` |

Report: pass count, fail count, skip count.

### 4. Structural health

```bash
strata check
strata lint --quiet
```

Report: pass/fail, error count, warning count.

### 5. Documentation freshness

```bash
strata lint --rule stale-dates --rule context-freshness
```

Report: any stale documentation or generated files.

## Output Format

```
STATUS: [project name]
========================================

Git:     clean, on main, up to date with origin
Build:   OK (no errors)
Tests:   197 passed, 0 failed
Strata:  check OK, lint 0 errors / 2 warnings
Docs:    1 stale date (MEMORY.md last_verified: 2026-03-01)

Overall: HEALTHY [or NEEDS ATTENTION]
```

## Anti-Examples

| Bad | Why | Better |
|-----|-----|--------|
| Running status checks manually one by one | Slow, easy to forget one | Run the full checklist |
| Ignoring warnings | Warnings accumulate into errors | Address warnings before they compound |
| Checking only what you're about to change | Broken tests elsewhere block your commits | Check everything quickly |
| Running full status during time-critical work | Overkill for a hotfix | Skip tests and docs checks when speed matters |

## Quality Self-Check

1. All 5 checks ran?
2. Overall assessment matches the findings?
3. Actionable items identified (not just "2 warnings")?
